DOCUMENT();

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
#           "PGstandard.pl",
#           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
#           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
#           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "MathObjects.pl",
#           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
          # "parserNumberWithUnits.pl",
          # "parserFormulaWithUnits.pl",
          # "parserFormulaUpToConstant.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
"AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
          );

TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");

@a = ( "\frac{\pi}{4}", "\frac{3 \pi}{4}", "\frac{5 \pi}{4}",
       "\frac{\pi}{3}", "\frac{\pi}{6}", "\frac{2 \pi}{3}",
       "\frac{ 5 \pi}{6}" );
$i = random(0,6,1);
@z = (45, 135, 225, 60, 30, 120, 150);

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;


Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
An angle of \( \displaystyle $a[$i] \) radians can be converted to an angle of \{ ans_rule(5) \} degrees.
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("numbers") \}
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS(Compute("$z[$i]")->cmp() );

#ANS(num_cmp( $z[$i] ) );


Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$PAR

In order to change from radians to degrees, we multiply the number of
radians by \( \frac{180}{\pi} \), so we have
$PAR
\( $a[$i] \cdot \frac{180}{\pi} = $z[$i]^{\circ} \)
$BR
END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;


COMMENT('MathObject version');
ENDDOCUMENT();
